    <h2>2.1 Why is Tesla's P/E Ratio Much Higher Than Apple's?</h2>
    
    <h3>üìå The Reasons</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Apple (AAPL)</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Mature company with slowing growth but stable profits.</li>
                <li>P/E ratio typically ranges between 25‚Äì30.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Tesla (TSLA)</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>High-growth company with high investor expectations for the future.</li>
                <li>Even with modest profits, the market gives it <strong>a very high P/E multiple (40‚Äì60+)</strong> because investors believe it will expand rapidly in the future.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>üëâ <strong>Summary</strong>Ôºö</p>
    <p>High P/E ‚â† the company is necessarily more profitable, but rather the market is willing to pay a higher premium for "future growth".</p>
    
    <h2>2.2 The Three Major Financial Statements: The Company's "Health Report"</h2>
    
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/IMG_5756.jpeg" alt="Financial Statements Overview" style="max-width: 600px;">
    </figure>
    
    <p><a href="https://www.xiaohongshu.com/explore/65969c1a000000001d02aa27">How to Quickly Read a Public Company's Financial Report in 5 Minutes?</a></p>
    
    <h1>üìä Income Statement</h1>
    <p><a href="https://www.xiaohongshu.com/explore/67ed2394000000001e005063">Understanding a Public Company's Income Statement in 2 Minutes</a></p>
    
    <ul>
        <li>Shows: <strong>how much money the company made during a specific period</strong>.</li>
        <li>Main structure:
            <ol>
                <li>Revenue</li>
                <li>Gross Profit (Revenue ‚Äì Cost)</li>
                <li>Operating Income</li>
                <li><strong>Operating Expenses</strong></li>
                <li>Net Income</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üìå Gross Profit Margin</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö
            <figure>
                <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image.png" alt="Gross Profit Margin Formula" style="max-width: 288px;">
            </figure>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Gross Profit</strong> = Revenue ‚Äì Cost of Goods Sold (e.g., production costs, material costs).</li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Measures <strong>the profitability of the product itself</strong>.</li>
                <li>High gross margin ‚Üí the product has pricing power, indicating strong brand or technological moat.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Apple (iPhone): Gross margin ~43%</li>
                <li>Costco: Gross margin ~12%, but wins through scale</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üìå Net Profit Margin</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö
            <figure>
                <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%201.png" alt="Net Profit Margin Formula" style="max-width: 288px;">
            </figure>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Net Profit</strong> = Gross Profit ‚Äì Operating Expenses ‚Äì Financial Expenses ‚Äì Taxes.</li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Measures how much money the company <strong>can ultimately retain</strong>.</li>
                <li>High net margin ‚Üí good cost control, healthier business model.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Microsoft: Net margin ~30% (low marginal cost for software)</li>
                <li>Walmart: Net margin ~2‚Äì3% (intense competition in retail)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>‚ùå Common Misconceptions</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Misconception 1: Higher gross margin = the company must be more profitable.
            <ul>
                <li>Example: Luxury companies have high gross margins, but may have low net profits due to high advertising and R&D expenses.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Misconception 2: Low net margin = bad company.
            <ul>
                <li>Example: Walmart's net margin is only 2‚Äì3%, but due to its massive scale, it's still one of the world's most profitable retail companies.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>‚úÖ Correct Understanding</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Gross Margin</strong>: Reflects the "per-unit profitability" of products, indicating whether the company has pricing power.</li>
        <li><strong>Net Margin</strong>: Reflects how much money the company "ultimately retains", indicating management and cost control levels.</li>
        <li><strong>Investment Logic</strong>: You need to look at both gross margin and net margin together to judge the true quality of a company's profitability.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h1>üíµ Cash Flow Statement</h1>
    
    <p><a href="http://xhslink.com/o/TvJhkd0zax">One Video to Understand Corporate Cash Flow Statement</a><br>
    <a href="https://www.xiaohongshu.com/explore/67f099f7000000001d01916c">Understanding Cash Flow Statement in 3 Minutes</a></p>
    
    <h2>üìå Definition</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>The Cash Flow Statement reflects the company's <strong>cash receipts and payments</strong> during a specific period.</li>
        <li>It answers the question:
            <ul>
                <li>Is the money the company earned real cash?</li>
                <li>Or just "paper profits"?</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>üëâ Analogy: The Income Statement is like a "report card", while the Cash Flow Statement is a "bank statement". The report card can look good, but the bank balance is what matters.</p>
    
    <h2>üìä Three Main Components</h2>
    
    <h3>1Ô∏è‚É£ Operating Cash Flow (OCF)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Source</strong>: Cash generated from core business operations.</li>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong> (simplified): <strong>Operating Cash Flow = Net Income + Non-cash Expenses (e.g., depreciation) + Changes in Working Capital</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>: Measures whether the core business is "generating cash".</li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Apple: Operating cash flow ~ $110 billion/year ‚Üí very healthy.</li>
                <li>Some startups: Net income is positive, but OCF is negative ‚Üí can't collect cash, relying on credit.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%202.png" alt="Operating Cash Flow" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    
    <h3>2Ô∏è‚É£ Investing Cash Flow (ICF)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Source</strong>: Investment, acquisition, and asset disposal activities.</li>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong> (simplified): Investing Cash Flow = Cash Inflow from Investment Recovery ‚àí Capital Expenditure</li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>: Reflects the company's investment in expansion, M&A, and R&D.</li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Tesla: Invests heavily in building Gigafactories each year ‚Üí investing cash flow is usually negative.</li>
                <li>TSMC: Massive capital expenditure (CapEx) ‚Üí investing cash flow is negative long-term, but future capacity increases.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3Ô∏è‚É£ Financing Cash Flow (FCF)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Source</strong>: Company financing and dividends.</li>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong> (simplified): Financing Cash Flow = Borrowing + Stock Issuance ‚àí Debt Repayment ‚àí Dividends</li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>: Shows whether the company relies on "borrowing" to survive.</li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>SoFi: Continuously raised funds in early stages (cash inflow), but as business stabilizes, gradually relies on its own cash flow.</li>
                <li>Coca-Cola: Stable long-term dividends ‚Üí financing cash flow is often negative.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%203.png" alt="Investing and Financing Cash Flow" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    
    <h2>üìå Free Cash Flow (FCF)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>: Free Cash Flow = Operating Cash Flow ‚àí Capital Expenditure</li>
        <li><strong>Significance</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>The cash the company can "freely use".</li>
                <li>Investors pay special attention ‚Üí because this is the real cash that can be used for dividends, buybacks, and reinvestment.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Examples</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Apple: Free cash flow $100 billion ‚Üí enough for dividends + stock buybacks.</li>
                <li>Netflix: Had negative free cash flow for a long time due to investment in original content, but later turned positive.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>‚ö†Ô∏è Common Misconceptions</h2>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Misconception 1: Positive net income = cash flow must be good</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Some companies use "accounting tricks" to make profits look good, but actually can't collect cash.</li>
                <li>Example: Some real estate companies show paper profits, but cash flow is negative long-term.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Misconception 2: Negative investing cash flow = bad company</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Many growth companies in expansion phase have negative investing cash flow, which is actually good (shows they're building factories/R&D).</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Misconception 3: Positive financing cash flow = healthy</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Some companies rely on debt to maintain operations, which actually increases risk.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ol>
    
    <h2>‚úÖ Correct Understanding</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Priority order for cash flow</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Operating Cash Flow > 0</strong> = healthy core business.</li>
                <li><strong>Investing Cash Flow < 0</strong> = investing in the future.</li>
                <li><strong>Free Cash Flow > 0</strong> = can really give money to shareholders.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Investment Logic</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>If a company has <strong>high profits but poor cash flow</strong> ‚Üí be careful.</li>
                <li>If a company has low profits but strong cash flow ‚Üí the model may be more stable.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h1>üìò Balance Sheet</h1>
    
    <h2>üìå Definition</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Balance Sheet</strong> = a snapshot of the company's financial position at a specific point in time.</li>
        <li>It answers the questions:
            <ul>
                <li>What "assets" does the company have now? (Assets)</li>
                <li>How much debt does it owe? (Liabilities)</li>
                <li>How much do shareholders actually own? (Shareholders' Equity)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>üëâ Analogy: The Income Statement is like a "report card" (performance over a period), while the Balance Sheet is a "bankbook + IOUs" (the company's real financial position today).</p>
    
