    <h2>üìä Structure</h2>
    
    <h3>1Ô∏è‚É£ Assets</h3>
    <p>Resources <strong>owned by the company</strong>, can be divided into:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Current Assets</strong> (can be converted to cash within one year): Cash, Accounts Receivable, Inventory</li>
        <li><strong>Non-current Assets</strong> (held long-term): Plant, Equipment, Patents, Long-term Investments</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2Ô∏è‚É£ Liabilities</h3>
    <p>Money <strong>owed to others</strong>, obligations to repay:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Current Liabilities</strong> (due within one year): Accounts Payable, Short-term Debt</li>
        <li><strong>Long-term Liabilities</strong> (due after one year): Long-term Loans, Bonds</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3Ô∏è‚É£ Shareholders' Equity</h3>
    <p>Company's "net worth" ‚Üí shareholders' true share.</p>
    
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%208.png" alt="Shareholders' Equity" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    
    <p>üëâ Simple understanding:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>You buy a house worth $1 million (asset), take a loan of $700,000 (liability), and you put in $300,000 yourself (shareholders' equity).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>üìå Important Formulas</h2>
    
    <h3><strong>Accounting Equation</strong></h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%209.png" alt="Accounting Equation" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    <p>This is the fundamental law of accounting, always true.</p>
    
    <h3><strong>Debt Ratio</strong></h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%2010.png" alt="Debt Ratio Formula" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Measures the company's leverage level.</li>
        <li>High ‚Üí high risk; Low ‚Üí stable.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3><strong>Current Ratio</strong></h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%2011.png" alt="Current Ratio Formula" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Measures the company's short-term debt-paying ability.</li>
        <li>1 ‚Üí theoretically can pay off short-term debt.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3><strong>Quick Ratio</strong></h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/financial-statements/image%2012.png" alt="Quick Ratio Formula" style="max-width: 100%;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>A stricter short-term debt-paying indicator (because inventory may not be sellable).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>üìå Case Studies</h2>
    
    <h3>üçè Apple (2023)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Total Assets: $352 billion</li>
        <li>Total Liabilities: $294 billion</li>
        <li>Shareholders' Equity: $58 billion</li>
        <li>Debt Ratio: ‚âà 83%</li>
        <li><strong>Conclusion</strong>: Apple has significant debt, but strong cash flow can fully cover it.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üöó Tesla (2023)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Total Assets: $105 billion</li>
        <li>Total Liabilities: $36 billion</li>
        <li>Shareholders' Equity: $69 billion</li>
        <li>Debt Ratio: ‚âà 34%</li>
        <li><strong>Conclusion</strong>: Tesla has relatively low debt, expansion relies more on equity financing.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üè¶ Ping An of China (A-share financial company)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Characteristic: Financial companies generally have high debt ratios (banks and insurance companies essentially "borrow short and lend long").</li>
        <li>Debt ratio > 90%, but this is an industry characteristic.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>‚ö†Ô∏è Common Misconceptions</h2>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Misconception 1: High debt ratio = dangerous company</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Some industries are naturally high-debt (banks, real estate), which doesn't mean unhealthy.</li>
                <li>Correct: Need to consider cash flow and industry characteristics.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Misconception 2: Small shareholders' equity = company is worthless</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Light-asset companies (like Google, Meta) have valuable brands and data, but assets aren't significant on the balance sheet.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Misconception 3: Higher current ratio is always better</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>‚ùå Wrong: Too high may indicate the company has too much idle cash, low efficiency.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ol>
    
    <h2>‚úÖ Correct Understanding</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Debt is not bad</strong>: Reasonable debt can amplify returns.</li>
        <li><strong>Look at structure</strong>: Short-term debt vs long-term debt, which has a higher proportion?</li>
        <li><strong>Combine the three statements</strong>Ôºö
            <ul>
                <li>Income Statement tells you if it's profitable.</li>
                <li>Cash Flow Statement tells you if money is coming in.</li>
                <li>Balance Sheet tells you if the foundation is stable.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
