    <h2>üìò Summary</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Balance Sheet = snapshot of company health</strong>.</li>
        <li>Three core indicators: Debt Ratio, Current Ratio, Quick Ratio.</li>
        <li>Investment should consider industry characteristics, don't mechanically look at numbers.</li>
        <li>An excellent company is often not "debt-free", but "uses debt in the right places".</li>
        <li>Reflects: what the company <strong>owns (assets)</strong>, what it <strong>owes (liabilities)</strong>, and what belongs to shareholders (shareholders' equity).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>2.3 Relationships Between the Three Statements</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>The "Net Income" from the Income Statement flows into the "Operating Cash Flow" of the Cash Flow Statement.</li>
        <li>The "Capital Expenditure" in the Cash Flow Statement affects "Fixed Assets" in the Balance Sheet.</li>
        <li>The "Shareholders' Equity" in the Balance Sheet corresponds to "Retained Earnings" from the Income Statement.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>üëâ <strong>Simple understanding</strong>Ôºö</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Income Statement = company's profit report card</li>
        <li>Cash Flow Statement = whether money actually came in</li>
        <li>Balance Sheet = how much "assets" the company has now</li>
    </ul>
    
